01:18:22,874 --> 01:18:25,169
[CHUCKLING]

1161
01:18:33,407 --> 01:18:34,600
No, it's not gonna work.

1162
01:18:35,107 --> 01:18:39,562
I feel like I'm trying on a new pair of shoes
I really wanna buy, but they just don't fit.

1163
01:18:39,740 --> 01:18:41,467
Sorry.

1164
01:18:41,774 --> 01:18:46,298
All right then, how about
going barefoot for a while?

1165
01:19:07,141 --> 01:19:09,130
[RAIN PATTERING]

1166
01:19:13,941 --> 01:19:18,566
WILLIAM: There's no man, alive or dead,
who's gonna fault you for living.

1167
01:19:19,708 --> 01:19:22,106
You're very sweet.

1168
01:19:23,975 --> 01:19:28,464
He was a good man, I reckon,
your man who died.

1169
01:19:29,175 --> 01:19:30,800
Yes...

1170
01:19:31,674 --> 01:19:33,663
...a very good man.

1171
01:19:41,708 --> 01:19:43,299
- William?
- Hmm?

1172
01:19:44,375 --> 01:19:48,000
Could you drive me to Enniskerry
in the morning?

1173
01:19:48,175 --> 01:19:49,573
Sure.

1174
01:19:50,075 --> 01:19:51,507
You got friends there?

1175
01:19:51,674 --> 01:19:54,402
Family. Sort of.

1176
01:19:54,875 --> 01:19:57,773
- In-laws. I should see them.
- Hmm.

1177
01:19:59,042 --> 01:20:01,668
What's their name? Maybe I know them.

1178
01:20:01,908 --> 01:20:03,340
The Kennedys.

1179
01:20:05,609 --> 01:20:08,200
Not Rose and Martin?

1180
01:20:08,609 --> 01:20:12,268
Yeah. You know them?

1181
01:20:16,675 --> 01:20:19,107
You're not Gerry's Holly?

1182
01:20:19,909 --> 01:20:20,932
What?

1183
01:20:21,275 --> 01:20:22,832
<i>Oh...</i>

1184
01:20:23,442 --> 01:20:25,533
You're the girl from the pub that night.

1185
01:20:26,575 --> 01:20:28,837
I was in Gerry's band.

1186
01:20:29,009 --> 01:20:31,134
Not Billy...

1187
01:20:31,309 --> 01:20:32,569
...Gallagher?
- One and the same.

1188
01:20:32,742 --> 01:20:33,730
[GASPS]

1189
01:20:34,309 --> 01:20:36,332
It's... It's all right.

1190
01:20:36,509 --> 01:20:38,873
It's all right. Me and Gerry,
we shared everything together.

1191
01:20:39,043 --> 01:20:40,304
[GASPS]

1192
01:20:40,476 --> 01:20:43,408
Oh, no, no, no, I didn't mean it like that.

1193
01:20:43,576 --> 01:20:46,769
What I meant was, you know,
he wouldn't have a <i>problem...</i>

1194
01:20:48,043 --> 01:20:50,134
Well, he might have a problem
but, you know...

1195
01:20:50,309 --> 01:20:53,173
...there's not much
he can do about it now, is there?

1196
01:20:55,343 --> 01:20:56,899
Holly.

1197
01:20:57,876 --> 01:21:00,900
Come here. Come back to bed.

1198
01:21:01,942 --> 01:21:04,238
Now, let's... Let's talk.

1199
01:21:07,309 --> 01:21:08,775
<i>Oh...</i>

1200
01:21:09,076 --> 01:21:11,235
I heard he died.

1201
01:21:13,176 --> 01:21:16,370
Tumor, was it? Yeah.

1202
01:21:17,144 --> 01:21:20,405
You know, Gerry and I, <i>we...</i>

1203
01:21:20,576 --> 01:21:24,406
We hadn't seen each other
in a long, long while.

1204
01:21:25,077 --> 01:21:27,599
It's sad when that happens
to best friends, isn't it?

1205
01:21:29,044 --> 01:21:30,032
[SIGHS]

1206
01:21:30,210 --> 01:21:34,074
<i>He...</i> He was a wonderful lad.

1207
01:21:37,310 --> 01:21:39,276
It's all right, you know.

1208
01:21:40,411 --> 01:21:42,172
It's okay.

1209
01:21:42,676 --> 01:21:44,938
You know, these things...

1210
01:21:45,444 --> 01:21:48,001
...they happen now and again.
Not very often...

1211
01:21:48,177 --> 01:21:49,370
[HOLLY CHUCKLES]

1212
01:21:49,577 --> 01:21:51,543
...but now and again.

1213
01:21:55,477 --> 01:21:58,409
Would you like me to tell you
some stories about me and Gerry?

1214
01:21:58,577 --> 01:22:00,509
I've got plenty.

1215
01:22:01,411 --> 01:22:02,809
Yeah?

1216
01:22:03,277 --> 01:22:06,402
Okay, here you go. Come on, sit back.

1217
01:22:11,210 --> 01:22:13,006
You know, he <i>was...</i>

1218
01:22:13,178 --> 01:22:15,609
He was my very, very best mate.

1219
01:22:16,245 --> 01:22:20,836
Starting back when we were terrors
running about at 5 and 6.

1220
01:22:21,045 --> 01:22:22,510
[LAUGHS]

1221
01:22:22,711 --> 01:22:24,768
Oh, he made me laugh.

1222
01:22:24,944 --> 01:22:27,910
There was this time,
I don't remember how old we were...

1223
01:22:28,078 --> 01:22:30,510
...probably, you know, 10, 11.

1224
01:22:31,278 --> 01:22:32,834
We jumped on a <i>train...</i>

1225
01:22:33,011 --> 01:22:34,102
[WILLIAM TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

1226
01:23:13,678 --> 01:23:15,667
[INAUDIBLE]

1227
01:23:22,779 --> 01:23:24,040
[PIANO PLAYING]

1228
01:23:24,212 --> 01:23:28,974
We received those packages you sent.
Come in. Come in.

1229
01:23:34,979 --> 01:23:36,036
Martin?

1230
01:23:37,679 --> 01:23:39,304
Look who it is.

1231
01:23:39,479 --> 01:23:42,411
Oh, well, look at that.

1232
01:23:42,579 --> 01:23:44,408
Come here, dear.

1233
01:23:44,613 --> 01:23:46,875
So nice to see you.

1234
01:23:47,646 --> 01:23:50,908
He was always one for writing.
Wasn't he?

1235
01:23:51,079 --> 01:23:52,477
Should've gone professional.

1236
01:23:52,646 --> 01:23:55,703
No. He did it for the love of it, Martin.

1237
01:23:56,246 --> 01:23:58,439
Now, where is it?

1238
01:23:58,713 --> 01:24:00,201
Oh, here it is.

1239
01:24:00,379 --> 01:24:04,539
"When Holly visits, take her
to my fort in the back yard...

1240
01:24:04,713 --> 01:24:06,338
...and give her this envelope."

1241
01:24:06,846 --> 01:24:09,437
He knew that I'd come visit you?

1242
01:24:09,746 --> 01:24:13,372
Hmm. Suppose he did. Heh. Martin.

1243
01:24:13,946 --> 01:24:15,378
All right.

1244
01:24:19,813 --> 01:24:23,302
It's not really a fort,
it's just a stone wall.

1245
01:24:23,480 --> 01:24:25,605
He used to call it that when he was little.

1246
01:24:27,780 --> 01:24:30,576
He goes on about other things...

1247
01:24:31,013 --> 01:24:32,536
...Iovely things.

1248
01:24:34,580 --> 01:24:38,909
He hadn't much strength in the end
though, did he?

1249
01:24:40,547 --> 01:24:44,206
Makes me sick to think
we weren't there when he died...

1250
01:24:44,380 --> 01:24:45,403
...for the funeral.

1251
01:24:45,580 --> 01:24:48,171
ROSE: But you could hardly walk
just after your operation.

1252
01:24:48,847 --> 01:24:53,041
Maybe you'll come and visit us a bit more
now that he's gone, eh?

1253
01:24:53,280 --> 01:24:55,303
Martin, don't put that on her.

1254
01:24:55,480 --> 01:24:57,639
You're under no obligation.

1255
01:24:57,814 --> 01:25:00,837
It's not like we're blood family.

1256
01:25:01,480 --> 01:25:03,571
I'd like to come visit.

1257
01:25:03,747 --> 01:25:07,611
And I'm sorry we didn't in the past. L...

1258
01:25:08,514 --> 01:25:12,242
I just thought you were angry with me
for taking Gerry away.

1259
01:25:12,415 --> 01:25:15,313
- She wanted you dead, you know.
- Martin, don't you dare!

1260
01:25:15,481 --> 01:25:17,639
No, I don't blame you.

1261
01:25:17,814 --> 01:25:21,247
You know, my mother, she never
quite got over the idea either.

1262
01:25:21,415 --> 01:25:25,904
Yeah, well, you were both so young.
And it happened too fast.

1263
01:25:27,715 --> 01:25:32,272
But Gerry loved you. I saw that.

1264
01:25:32,847 --> 01:25:34,780
I saw that.

1265
01:25:40,981 --> 01:25:44,311
GERRY: <i>To my Galway Girl:</i>
<i>You're an angel for seeing my folks.</i>

1266
01:25:44,481 --> 01:25:49,379
<i>I told you my mom didn't hate your guts.</i>
<i>Well, you know, anymore.</i>

1267
01:25:49,982 --> 01:25:54,437
<i>You are now standing in my fort</i>
<i>where I did all my big thinking.</i>

1268
01:25:54,615 --> 01:26:00,071
<i>This is where I stood thinking about you</i>
<i>after the very first time we met.</i>

1269
01:26:09,482 --> 01:26:12,175
<i>You didn't look real to me at first.</i>

1270
01:26:12,349 --> 01:26:15,213
<i>I never saw so many colors</i>
<i>on one girl before...</i>

1271
01:26:15,382 --> 01:26:18,212
<i>... but you looked like</i>
<i>you belonged out there, all right.</i>

1272
01:26:18,382 --> 01:26:20,711
<i>You and all your colors.</i>

1273
01:26:20,915 --> 01:26:24,040
<i>Do you remember</i>
<i>the first thing you ever said to me?</i>

1274
01:26:24,215 --> 01:26:25,738
I'm lost.

1275
01:26:25,915 --> 01:26:29,279
<i>Oh, you didn't look lost, not to me.</i>

1276
01:26:29,449 --> 01:26:31,642
So, what are you looking for out here?

1277
01:26:31,816 --> 01:26:34,839
Wicklow Mountains National Park?

1278
01:26:35,015 --> 01:26:36,003
[LAUGHS]

1279
01:26:36,182 --> 01:26:40,137
Wicklow Mountains National Park.
Tell me, how long you been walking for?

1280
01:26:40,315 --> 01:26:41,679
A few hours.

1281
01:26:41,849 --> 01:26:45,872
Well, you've probably been in
the national park for a few hours, then.

1282
01:26:46,182 --> 01:26:48,081
Oh, my God.

1283
01:26:48,449 --> 01:26:49,779
This is a park?

1284
01:26:49,949 --> 01:26:51,574
Uh-huh.

1285
01:26:53,150 --> 01:26:54,308
Oh.

1286
01:26:54,482 --> 01:26:55,846
It's so cold!

1287
01:26:56,016 --> 01:26:58,278
The paper said it was gonna be warm.

1288
01:26:58,449 --> 01:27:02,439
It is warm. I know you're lost, but
you do know you're in Ireland, don't you?

1289
01:27:04,350 --> 01:27:07,543
Well, I better head back. Heh.

1290
01:27:07,849 --> 01:27:14,407
- And where is that?
- I'm staying at a B and B in Dunlougahairy.

1291
01:27:14,583 --> 01:27:17,912
Dunlagohairy?
No, I think you mean Dún Laoghaire.

1292
01:27:18,083 --> 01:27:21,947
- Heh-heh. You're kidding?
- No. Would I lie to you?

1293
01:27:23,550 --> 01:27:26,744
- Dún Laoghaire?
- Dún Laoghaire.

1294
01:27:28,917 --> 01:27:31,906
Okay. Thanks.

1295
01:27:32,116 --> 01:27:33,742
You're grand.

1296
01:27:34,917 --> 01:27:37,144
But you're going the wrong way,
you know.

1297
01:27:42,984 --> 01:27:44,210
[SOFTLY]
That way?

1298
01:27:44,383 --> 01:27:45,940
[CHUCKLING]
Okay.

1299
01:27:46,117 --> 01:27:49,106
I think you quite enjoy this getting lost,
don't you?

1300
01:27:50,017 --> 01:27:54,211
You know, actually,
I don't mind so much, not here.

1301
01:27:54,917 --> 01:27:56,406
So how did you come to be here?

1302
01:27:56,583 --> 01:28:00,538
Oh, on my way home, college trip.
We started in Greece.

1303
01:28:00,717 --> 01:28:03,706
Jesus, that's a long walk.
That's a bad joke.

1304
01:28:03,884 --> 01:28:05,214
What are you studying?

1305
01:28:06,418 --> 01:28:08,577
- Art. Yeah.
- Art?

1306
01:28:08,750 --> 01:28:12,205
- Oh, so you're an artist, then?
- Oh. I don't know yet.

1307
01:28:12,651 --> 01:28:13,639
That's great.

1308
01:28:13,817 --> 01:28:14,805
[CHUCKLING]

1309
01:28:14,984 --> 01:28:16,916
Do you make anything or?

1310
01:28:18,518 --> 01:28:19,506
I don't know yet.

1311
01:28:19,684 --> 01:28:20,707
[BOTH CHUCKLING]

1312
01:28:20,884 --> 01:28:22,680
Well, good luck with that.

1313
01:28:25,418 --> 01:28:26,714
Oh.

1314
01:28:34,117 --> 01:28:35,674
<i>You...</i>

1315
01:28:35,851 --> 01:28:40,011
Would you mind if we walked together
since we're going in the same direction?

1316
01:28:40,185 --> 01:28:43,912
I'll stay on this side of the road.
Don't even have to talk. Just...

1317
01:28:44,751 --> 01:28:48,843
Just quite nice, sometimes walking
along with someone without talking...

1318
01:28:49,018 --> 01:28:51,882
...once you get your feet wet.

1319
01:29:03,485 --> 01:29:05,474
GERRY:
<i>At first, the no-talking thing didn't last.</i>

1320
01:29:05,652 --> 01:29:07,515
<i>Before long, I couldn't get you to shut up.</i>

1321
01:29:07,685 --> 01:29:14,174
<i>But you were so cute, trying to impress me</i>
<i>with William Blake and all your grand plans.</i>

1322
01:29:14,352 --> 01:29:16,511
<i>I had no idea</i>
<i>what you were talking about...</i>

1323
01:29:16,685 --> 01:29:19,583
<i>... but I couldn't help</i>
<i>loving the way you talked.</i>

1324
01:29:19,752 --> 01:29:23,275
"I must create a..."

1325
01:29:23,519 --> 01:29:27,849
Something."...or be enslaved
by another man's..." Something.

1326
01:29:28,019 --> 01:29:30,917
Wait, "I will <i>not...</i>

1327
01:29:31,152 --> 01:29:32,141
[GRUNTS]

1328
01:29:32,318 --> 01:29:35,751
I will not reason or compare.

1329
01:29:35,919 --> 01:29:38,749
My business is to <i>create..."</i>

1330
01:29:39,119 --> 01:29:41,710
- Something. Oh, God.
- Did you just make that up then?

1331
01:29:41,886 --> 01:29:45,545
No, it's William Blake,
but I completely screwed it up.

1332
01:29:45,719 --> 01:29:48,185
No, you didn't, you made it better.
I understood it.

1333
01:29:48,353 --> 01:29:49,818
GERRY:
<i>I didn't have a clue, actually.</i>

1334
01:29:49,986 --> 01:29:55,078
All I know is, if you don't figure out the
"something," you'll just stay ordinary.

1335
01:29:55,253 --> 01:30:01,015
And it doesn't matter if it's a work of art,
or a taco, or a pair of socks.

1336
01:30:01,219 --> 01:30:05,311
Just create something new
and there it is.

1337
01:30:05,486 --> 01:30:08,849
And it's you, out in the world,
outside of you.

1338
01:30:09,019 --> 01:30:13,145
And you can look at it, or hear it,
or read it, or feel it...

1339
01:30:13,319 --> 01:30:15,751
...and you know
a little bit more about you.

1340
01:30:15,920 --> 01:30:18,750
A little bit more than anybody else does.

1341
01:30:19,219 --> 01:30:20,879
Does that make any sense at all?

1342
01:30:22,486 --> 01:30:24,009
Yeah.

1343
01:30:24,586 --> 01:30:26,415
You're saying you want to paint socks.

1344
01:30:28,020 --> 01:30:29,747
Maybe.

1345
01:30:29,920 --> 01:30:31,011
[CHUCKLES]

1346
01:30:31,187 --> 01:30:33,379
GERRY:
<i>I loved you right then and there.</i>

1347
01:30:37,953 --> 01:30:40,181
HOLLY:
Hey, I like this jacket.

1348
01:30:41,486 --> 01:30:43,884
GERRY:
It looks good on you. Got it on a bet.

1349
01:30:44,054 --> 01:30:45,747
- What was the bet?
- Heh.

1350
01:30:46,553 --> 01:30:49,111
I was a few Guinness's
for the worse at this point...

1351
01:30:49,287 --> 01:30:52,481
...but a fella bet me
that I couldn't get a certain girl...

1352
01:30:52,653 --> 01:30:54,846
...to kiss me without a provocation.

1353
01:30:55,020 --> 01:30:57,509
- What girl?
- His girl.

1354
01:30:57,687 --> 01:30:59,380
- Oh! Ha-ha.
- Uh-huh. Ha-ha.

1355
01:30:59,554 --> 01:31:02,384
- How'd you do it?
- There's nothing to it, really.

1356
01:31:02,687 --> 01:31:06,676
A fella just has to tell a woman
the truth without words.

1357
01:31:06,854 --> 01:31:09,615
It's like a signal you send out.

1358
01:31:09,788 --> 01:31:11,777
The woman, she just picks it up.

1359
01:31:12,821 --> 01:31:14,184
And what's the truth?

1360
01:31:16,220 --> 01:31:20,550
That kissing her would be
the end of life as I know it.

1361
01:31:22,654 --> 01:31:24,018
Wow.

1362
01:31:25,521 --> 01:31:28,044
And that's true of every girl
you've gotten to kiss you?

1363
01:31:28,221 --> 01:31:29,379
[GERRY LAUGHS]

1364
01:31:29,754 --> 01:31:33,050
I could turn it on and off when I was
younger and I had no principles.

1365
01:31:33,221 --> 01:31:38,415
When every girl that I was lucky enough
to kiss was the end of life as I knew it.

1366
01:31:40,821 --> 01:31:42,253
And now?

1367
01:31:44,522 --> 01:31:49,147
Now I only send it out when I think
she might be the one that makes it true.

1368
01:31:58,789 --> 01:32:01,778
I know where I am now.
Thanks, it was really nice to meet you.

1369
01:32:01,954 --> 01:32:04,386
- No, I could walk you into town.
- Oh, no, it's okay.

1370
01:32:04,555 --> 01:32:07,487
I know where I am.
I know where I'm going.

1371
01:32:11,555 --> 01:32:13,384
I'll never forget this.

1372
01:32:18,455 --> 01:32:19,682
Your jacket.

1373
01:32:19,855 --> 01:32:21,844
[DOG BARKING]

1374
01:32:23,388 --> 01:32:24,786
No, wait!

1375
01:32:24,955 --> 01:32:26,420
[WHISPERING]
Wait, wait, don't move.

1376
01:32:26,588 --> 01:32:29,349
- What?
- Oh, yeah, it's a wild Irish dog.

1377
01:32:29,522 --> 01:32:30,510
- A what?
- Shh!

1378
01:32:31,588 --> 01:32:33,520
- You have to stand still.
- Okay.

1379
01:32:33,688 --> 01:32:37,848
Get close, like one person.

1380
01:32:38,022 --> 01:32:40,920
And if we separate, he'll feel...

1381
01:32:41,089 --> 01:32:43,680
...threatened and attack our vital parts.

1382
01:32:43,855 --> 01:32:46,753
- What vital parts? All my parts are vital.
- Shh, shh.

1383
01:32:47,056 --> 01:32:49,045
[BARKING THEN GROWLING]

1384
01:32:49,656 --> 01:32:51,087
GERRY:
We have to stand still.

1385
01:32:51,256 --> 01:32:54,086
Now, just let him sniff around a bit.

1386
01:32:54,389 --> 01:32:55,412
[SNIFFING]

1387
01:32:56,623 --> 01:32:57,918
GERRY:
Now wait.

1388
01:33:06,656 --> 01:33:08,713
[WHISPERING]
I'm really scared.

1389
01:33:08,890 --> 01:33:10,879
Would you put
your arms around me?

1390
01:33:11,057 --> 01:33:12,420
All right.

1391
01:33:12,589 --> 01:33:15,350
- Yeah, that's probably a good idea.
- Yeah.

1392
01:33:15,523 --> 01:33:16,989
[DOG PANTING]

1393
01:33:17,157 --> 01:33:21,782
Do you think we could turn around and
